<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ulmanis: U.S. Made No Secret Deals With Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101154594 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1400 GMT 21 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2101154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Latvian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At a press conference held today, Latvian President 
Guntis Ulmanis announced that his telephone conversation on 
Thursday with U.S. President Bill Clinton allows him to conclude 
that Moscow and Washington have no secret agreements that could 
threaten Latvia's sovereignty. 
  The U.S. President, in his 30-minute telephone conversation, 
emphasized that the issues of human rights and citizenship are 
not linked to the issue of the withdrawal of Russian troops. 
The United States, since the incident in Latvia on 10 January 
and the events connected with it, has not changed its stance on 
the issue of the withdrawal of Russian troops and believes that 
the issue of human rights and citizenship is to be settled by 
the Latvian state itself, stressed Guntis Ulmanis. 
  Bill Clinton also informed Ulmanis about his visit to Moscow 
last week. The U.S. President discussed with Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin the issue of the Skrunda radar station. Clinton 
recommended continuing talks at the level of the government 
commissions on this issue and seeking a compromise solution. 

</TEXT>

