<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Rejects Counterintelligence Rules </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2101212194 Tallinn BNS in English 1932 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2101212194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jan 21, BNS -- Latvian lawmakers rejected the 
Cabinet's Jan. 11 regulations on counterintelligence, thus 
approving the National Independence Movement's proposal. 
  The other 37 resolutions, which the government accepted in 
between the parliament sessions, were sent for consideration to 
the Saeima (parliament) standing committees. 
  The rejected rule stipulated the setup of 
counterintelligence 
services to prognosticate, monitor and neutralize any danger to 
the national security. The services were also designed to 
gather information on concrete candidates for important 
government posts. 
  A heated debate arose when considering the Cabinet 
resolutions on the Riga local government and the amendments to 
the law on the status of a local deputy. 
  As reported, the government adopted these norms Jan. 10 
after 
the conflict between local authorities and Russian officers. 
The rules allow for dismissing any local government head who 
repeatedly fails to observe laws or Cabinet resolutions. 
  The norms are inconsistent with the principles of a 
rule-of-law state, according to which an elected person is 
dismissed only by a court ruling, said Maris Budovskis, of the 
National Independence Movement faction. 
  If the Saeima had rejected the resolution, Andrejs Rucs, the 
fired Vidzeme district head, should have been restored in office. 

</TEXT>

