<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Approves 1994 Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2101132094 Tallinn BNS in English 1047 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2101132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jan 21, BNS -- The Latvian Saeima 
(parliament) adopted the 1994 budget plan Thursday [20 January] 
after its first reading. 
  The plan was endorsed by the ruling Latvia's Way - Farmers' 
Union coalition, the Concord for Latvia faction, the Democratic 
Party faction and the Equality of Rights (Lidztiesiba) faction. 
  The Latvian National Independence Movement faction, the 
Homeland and Freedom, and the Christian Democrats Union 
factions, however, proposed to postpone the approvement until 
the draft's "conceptual re-arrangement." 
  The budget lacks clearcut concepts for the defense sphere 
and 
the local administration, said Alexander Kirsteins of the 
Independence Movement. 
  The government adjusted the planned incomes to the 
chaotically developing economy, said Equality of Rights' Larisa 
Lavina, who objected to the plan's economic motivation. 
  On the other hand, the budget plan duly reflects "the budget 
of a small, economically haphazard country" that earns almost 
nothing from industry and foreign investments, said Concord's 
leader Edvins Kide. 
  The debate corresponded to the general world practice -- the 
ruling coalition tried to persuade the critical opposition into 
approving a project, said Andrejs Pantelejevs, the head of the 
Latvia's Way faction. 

</TEXT>

