<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Imposes Comprehensive Duty on Imports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1901154594 Tallinn BNS in English 1344 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1901154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jan 19, BNS -- The Latvian Cabinet passed 
regulations Tuesday [18 January] imposing an import duty on all 
foreign-made goods, Finance Minister Uldis Osis told reporters. 
  The resolution replaces the earlier order that allowed to 
waive import duties on certain categories of goods. The duty 
will vary from 15 percent to 20 percent depending on whether the 
exporter country has a free trade agreement with Latvia, Osis 
said. 
  The lowest tariff is levied on raw materials, which are 
being 
brought in to supply the local industry. 
  Imported products that can be made on the spot will be taxed 
45 percent, Osis said. 
  The tariffs are tailored to protect the domestic market, the 
minister noted. Simultaneously, Osis conceded, the tariffs 
increase alone is unable to protect the Latvian market. Latvia 
should also improve the tax collection mechanism and customs 
control, he said. 
  The new tariffs take effect 30 days after their publication 
in the LATVIJAS VESTNESIS newspaper. 
  In other actions, the Cabinet gave the go-ahead for the 
liquidation of a series of profitless state-run enterprises and 
adopted the order for repayment of excise taxes on diesel fuel, 
which were earlier paid by Latvian farmers in accordance with an 
erroneous government resolution. 

</TEXT>

