<H3> <TI>   Shcherbakov Favored as Replacement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401153894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1408 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401153894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] As INTERFAX has learned from a reliable source, 
Finance Minister Boris Fedorov and the "Interprivatization Fund" 
president Vladimir Shcherbakov had a meeting in the first half 
of the day on Monday. A 45-year-old economist and first deputy 
prime minister in the former USSR cabinet, Shcherbakov has 
lately been favored as the possible new finance minister. 
  According to unconfirmed reports, the two men agreed that 
since the financial situation in the country "is extremely 
tense," a finance minister should also be a first deputy prime 
minister. 
  Shcherbakov is reported to have been trying to persuade 
Fedorov to drop his tough demands on the cabinet's makeup and 
stay in the government. 

