<H3> <TI>   Fedorov Denies Seeking Foreign Post </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101135994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1231 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yuriy Sizov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 21 TASS -- Boris Fedorov, who has 
resigned as finance minister from the Russian Government, denied 
mass media reports that he is seeking a job in an influential 
foreign organisation. 
  He told TASS on Friday that a publication of the British 
"GUARDIAN" newspaper which claimed that he had asked US 
Ambassador in Russia Thomas Pickering to find a job for him in 
an influential international organisation was a "provocation". 
  "I have not been in the US Embassy for several months and I 
was not even present at the meeting with US President Bill 
Clinton in Spaso House on December 14 although I was invited to 
it", Fedorov said. 
  He added that he would now focus on his work as State Duma 
deputy to draft lawbills boosting reforms. 

</TEXT>

