<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Says Cabinet To Meet More Often </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101161494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1403 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101161494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, speaking 
at the first session of his new cabinet on Friday, said it would 
meet more often, possibly twice a week, now that it was trimmed 
down, government spokesman Valentin Sergeyev told reporters. 
  The Prime Minister stressed that although the new government 
was cut by 20 percent, this will not affect its performance 
because of the professional skills of its members. 
  He told senior cabinet members that the government must 
build 
its relations with the Federal Assembly on the basis of 
cooperation, given that the cabinet and parliament were being 
led by "common state interests." 
  Chernomyrdin had accepted a proposal made at the session of 
the State Duma that the government should make weekly reports in 
the house. In his view, the prime minister or his deputies do 
not have to appear regularly in parliament but cabinet members 
and ministers must keep in permanent touch with the deputies. 
  Chernomyrdin stressed in particular that members of the 
reformed cabinet should not pay much attention to forecasts of 
"how long it will last, given that the present government is 
quite viable". 
  It was decided that the government would meet in a full 
session on February 17, with President Yeltsin possibly 
attending it. 
  Chernomyrdin warned the ministries and departments against 
any excessive spending while forming this year's budget. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

