<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin, Chernomyrdin Hold Unscheduled Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401115994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1052 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Yeltsin and Prime Minister Chernomyrdin 
had a meeting in the Kremlin on Monday. As a presidential 
spokesman told INTERFAX, the meeting was not planned. 
  Although he declined to say what the two leaders had 
discussed, he suggested that they had continued to examine the 
problems related to cabinet reorganization. 
  He said that the unexpected flow of criticism to the 
government reshuffle had been staggering for them in many ways. 
So they might have made a new attempt to choose a new finance 
minister and possibly reach a compromise with Fedorov. 
  As for the recent speculations about the possible 
appointment 
to the post of finance minister of ex-USSR premier Scherbakov, 
the spokesman described them "as an attempt to sound out the 
president and the prime minister on this candidate." 

</TEXT>

