<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Democratic Russia Questions Cabinet Reshuffle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2301154194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1311 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2301154194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Representatives of the Democratic Russia Movement 
[DRM] ended a meeting in Moscow on Saturday [22 January] by 
expressing "anxiety and concern" over the President's 
endorsement of a new government which they described as "an 
incomprehensible step". 
  Their appeal to Yeltsin says that unlike Belarus, Ukraine 
and 
Uzbekistan and other republics of the former Soviet Union, 
Russia has acquired steady reformists such Yegor Gaydar, 
Anatoliy Chubays and Boris Fedorov due to your personal 
involvement. The DRM is now puzzled over Yeltsin's support to 
the upholders of the idea of "squeezing" members of the 
reformist wing out of the government to please "red" monopoly 
directors with Viktor Chernomyrdin in charge. DRM leaders accuse 
Yeltsin of backing up what is in essence is a new "Soviet 
government". 
  Participants in the meeting reminded Yeltsin of his verbal 
commitment to "the policy of radical reforms" he had expressed 
at a recent news conference during U.S. president Bill Clinton's 
visit to Moscow. However, they said, Prime Minister 
Chernomyrdin announcing the make up of a new cabinet "made it 
clear the pattern of reforms would be corrected". 
  DRM has warned Yeltsin of intending to put up resistance to 
the new economic policy leading to the winding up of reforms. 
  The appeal ends with a question to the President: "What is 
your own policy, Boris Nikolayevich?" 

</TEXT>

