<DOCNO> FBIS3-57140 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov015_b_94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-015 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Choice Pessimistic on New Cabinet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101133994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1252 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 21 TASS -- "The Russia's Choice 
faction has not yet decided on whether it should oppose all the 
government or not, but, in general, it has little optimism 
concerning the cabinet's new composition," ITAR-TASS was told 
today by faction member Kirill Ignatyev. 
  In his opinion, the new cabinet will prove to be a 
government 
of inflation. This is why the Russia's Choice faction cannot 
assume the responsibility for all its work. "The faction," 
Ignatyev said, "will apparently oppose some steps of the 
government, maybe even many, while supporting only two areas 
--privatisation, for which Anatoliy Chubays is responsible, and 
the international policy. 
  "When we recommended Andrey Kozyrev, who is a member of the 
Russia's Choice movement, to stay on in the government, we were 
guided by the conviction that the Zhirinovskiy policy called for 
a serious, competent and balanced alternative, capable of 
preventing extremism from getting the upper hand," Ignatyev 
stated. 
  Economist Pavel Bunich, also a member of the Russia's Choice 
faction, told ITAR-TASS that the the formation of the new 
cabinet tended, without doubt, to reduce the vector of economic 
reforms. But this, in his opinion, could partially produce some 
rather sound results. "The point is," Bunich said, "that 
inflation was slightly checked by means of both sound and 
unsound means. Combatting inflation by not paying wages to 
people was an impermissible method, while the restriction of 
credits and subsidies to poorly functioning enterprises was a 
positive measure. It will only be for the good of the nation if 
the new government manages to do away with this harmful aspect 
of combatting inflation," the economist believes. 
  "Radicalism's attenuation in this sphere should be 
welcomed," 
he added. "However, regretful though it may be, the scales may 
be tilted further towards greater inflation," Bunich stressed. 
"Today," he believes, "there is a state of temporary balance. 
There is now an axis between the president, premier, and 
chairmen of the two chambers of the parliament. But as soon as 
inflation soars up, attempts will immediately be made to find a 
scapegoat. The parliament will point to the government, and so 
will the president. Therefore, it cannot be ruled out that the 
question of the cabinet's inefficiency will be raised within a 
matter of four months from now. At present, the situation within 
the government largely depends on the behaviour of the premier. 
Whereas formerly we used to claim that it depends more on Yegor 
Gaydar and Boris Fedorov, today we are witnessing the emergence 
of a one-man theatre." 
  Leader of the Russian Communist Party faction Gennadiy 
Zyuganov told ITAR-TASS that a very difficult struggle was being 
fought over the new government. "At least two loyal associates 
of Gaydar -- Anatoliy Chubays and Andrey Kozyrev -- are now 
holding key posts in it," he added. "It remains to be seen 
whether the new line will prevail, the line aimed at stabilising 
and normalising our work, when workers and commodity producers 
will be encouraged, or we shall again get a compromise hybrid, 
which will not yield anything positive," Zyuganov stated. In 
his opinion, this is the crux of the ongoing struggle. "For the 
time being, it appears that the pragmatic line is getting the 
upper hand," Zyuganov stated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

