<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Burbulis Warns Yeltsin Could Be Isolated </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101171994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1536 
GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2101171994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Velichko and Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 21 Jan -- "The most alarming thing of all 
happening in society is the real danger for the president of the 
Russian Federation becoming isolated from those who were 
professionally involved in implementing democratic reform and 
from their support," Gennadiy Burbulis, a State Duma deputy from 
the Russia's Choice Bloc, told ITAR-TASS correspondents in an 
interview. 
  "It is necessary to persuade the president that unless he 
relies on a clear and definite support from reformers, he risks 
finding himself in isolation," he said. "In that case, serious 
shocks may occur, including the hysteria around a possible 
resignation of the government." We must do all we can to 
prevent Boris Yeltsin from becoming alienated and isolated, he 
added. 
  Burbulis considers that the government, with its present 
composition, "has the resources and the country has the 
professionals to continue reform-oriented policies." As for the 
reform strategy itself, "it is in danger but not fatally so." 
  Burbulis did not rule out that "many work collectives might 
seriously express their discontent" in April and May. However, 
the president and the government are in a position to prevent 
this happening. "A search for mechanisms of social and 
professional rehabilitation of the workers who are under threat 
of lay-offs should start today," he stressed. 

</TEXT>

