<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gaydar Calls For Reconstruction of Democratic Movement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2201175794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1635 
GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2201175794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 22 January -- Today Yegor Gaydar made an 
appeal to the participants of an assembly of Moscow's democratic 
community for a serious reconstruction of the democratic 
movement. 
  He made a speech in which he explained his reasons for 
leaving the government. Yegor Gaydar gave as one of his reasons 
for resigning the government's adoption of a decision to 
allocate $500 million toward the construction of a new 
parliament building. In his words, "To carry out a policy 
envisaging the adoption of such decisions is to go beyond the 
bounds of morality." 
  Yegor Gaydar believes that the disagreements that were 
clearly visible in the work of the government over the past year 
were linked to the fundamental question of "what kind of Russia 
we want to have." He explained that the reformers favored a 
"cheap and moderately sized state that serves society," and in 
particular, reducing the state apparatus and bringing to a 
minimum the number of government functionaries. However, there 
exists another approach in Russia as well, he said. This is "a 
strong, powerful, and expensive state, which will intervene in 
all spheres of public life and will have a powerful apparatus of 
functionaries merging with a new emerging bourgeoisie." 
  Nevertheless, Yegor Gaydar said that Russia's Choice was 
ready to support any constructive decisions by the government. 
  Answering a question from an ITAR-TASS correspondent on the 
future work of Anatoliy Chubays in the government, Yegor Gaydar 
said that "it will be difficult for Chubays to work." He 
explained that "the privatization process has gathered a certain 
momentum, and if people begin actively and systematically to 
wreck it, it will nevertheless continue until 1 July, when 
privatization checks expire." Yegor Gaydar expressed the hope 
that Anatoliy Chubays "will do all he can to fulfill our 
obligations." 
  The participants at the assembly supported the creation of a 
New Civic Movement. It will be formed on the basis of 
Democratic Russia. The adopted manifesto of the New Civic 
Movement [Novoye Grazhdanskoye Dvizheniye] proclaims the need 
"to build a civic society by peaceful means, improve the 
socio-economic situation of working people, and ensure a normal 
standard of living for ourselves and our children." 
  Lev Ponomarev, co-chairman of the Democratic Russia 
movement, 
said that the movement's founding conference should be held as 
early as the beginning of March. 

</TEXT>

