<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gaydar Comments on Yeltsin, Russia's Choice </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101133494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1130 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The president wants to continue the reforms but has 
to adapt to reality, in particular the December election 
results, former deputy prime minister Yegor Gaydar, who leads 
the Russia's Choice group in parliament, told INTERFAX. 
  "If the democrats had been united and had run the election 
campaign better, the president would be in a better position 
now," he said. 
  Gaydar, who intends to concentrate on parliamentary work 
now, 
emphasized that Russia's Choice had to formulate a clear-cut 
position for itself. "There was uncertainty about the position 
of our parliamentary group when it could not be said for sure if 
we are in power or in opposition and we were held responsible 
for decisions which we did not make," he said. Now, he said, 
the group was in constructive opposition and could criticize the 
cabinet. 
  Gaydar dismissed rumors of a split in the group. Only two 
men, Andrey Makarov and Boris Fedorov, left for the December 12 
Union, a group "which votes almost the way we do." He thought 
that for a group of 78 this did not amount to a split. 
  Commenting on the latest Duma decisions Gaydar said: "It is 
funny that the Duma discussed so thoroughly the well-being of 
the deputies and 'lavish' provisions for them were advocated by 
the communists and other left-wing parties. Despite the 
resistance mounted by Russia's Choice and my own speeches they 
secured a resounding victory in this issue." 

</TEXT>

