<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pro-Democracy Groups Form New Civic Movement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401120594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1052 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pro-democracy groups meeting in Moscow on Saturday 
announced creation of a new Civic Movement. 
  They issued a manifesto saying the democrats sustained a 
crushing defeat in last month's general elections. 
  For the past two years, it says, pro-democracy groups have 
supported the new establishment and the president though being 
aware of their weakness and mistakes. "But we were also aware of 
something even worse than that -- the establishment's growing 
indifference to the electorate," says the manifesto. 
  The authors of the manifesto speak of a dramatic change with 
"alienation between the government and the people reaching any 
acceptable limits." 
  "Amid continuing hardships caused by economic crisis, this 
is 
fraught with social upheavals," it says. 
  The authors called for an alternative policy of reforms to 
the benefit of the people. 
  The manifesto says the country still has a chance to build a 
civilian society peacefully, create a robust middle class, 
redress the plight of hired workers, and give each honest man an 
opportunity to ensure a decent standard of living for himself 
and his family. 

</TEXT>

