<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Advisers Resign Over Policy Disagreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101204494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1913 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101204494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Economic advisers to the Russian government Anders 
Oslund of the Stockholm School of Economics and Jeffrey Sachs of 
Harvard University have sent a letter to President Yeltsin 
saying they refuse further work. 
  The two experts spoke of not wanting to help the Russian 
government further because "the Prime Minister-declared aims are 
entirely out of line with our personal views." They fear that 
with the arrival of the new Russian government, the situation 
will exacerbate following further inflation, already among the 
world's highest. 
  Pointing to austerity measures carried out by Estonia, 
Latvia 
and Poland, which succeeded in curbing inflation, Oslund and 
Sachs expressed the hope for a successful reform in Russia. 
They also spoke of wanting to work on a personal basis with 
reform supporters and a new generation of Russian pro-market 
economists. 
  To avoid a diversion from the course of reforms, the new 
government ought to include competent people not lobbyists such 
as Vice Premier Aleksandr Zaveryukha, Oslund told Interfax. 
Oslund and Sachs have worked for the Russian government since 
1991. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

