<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shokhin Urges Economics Ministry Role in Reforms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101182494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1703 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101182494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In an exclusive interview with INTERFAX today, 
Russian Economics Minister Aleksandr Shokhin said that the 
Economics Ministry he heads should play the key part in shaping 
up the strategy of reforms. 
  Shokhin believes that the Economics Ministry should not only 
calculate the effects of economic decisions, but also "thrust 
quite explicit variants of economic policy on the government." 
  Following the changes in the government's structure and 
personal composition, the ministry should take up coordinating 
the policies towards both domestic and foreign investments, 
Shokhin said. Therefore, the functions of the Russian Agency for 
International Cooperation and Development which earlier 
attracted foreign investments must be transferred to the 
Economics Ministry. 
  In addition, the ministry will focus on the maintenance of 
financial proportions in the economy and access to the world 
market, according to Shokhin. 
  Commenting on Boris Fedorov's resignation, Shokhin noted: 
"Boris Grigoryevich put himself in quite an uncomfortable 
position by making a number of wittingly uncompromising demands 
formulated in quite an indelicate manner." 
  Fedorov made the resignation of Vice Prime Minister 
Aleksandr 
Zaveryukha and Central Bank Chairman Viktor Geraschenko a 
condition to his work in the reorganized government. 
  "It seems to me that the main thing Boris Fedorov could 
demand from the president and the prime minister was pursuing a 
certain course of financial policy and make this a condition to 
his stay in the government only," the minister said. 
  "If Boris Fedorov sincerely believed that Geraschenko and 
Zaveryukha hampered the reforms, the need for Fedorov's presence 
in the government as a counterbalance to these people must be 
even stronger," Shokhin is convinced. 
  "I do not think that the life of the present government may 
shorten due to the absence of Gaydar and Fedorov," Shokhin 
pointed out adding that "everything will depend on the line the 
cabinet will be pursuing." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

