<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gaydar Hopes Economic Achievements Will Not Be Lost </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2301171394 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1400 GMT 
23 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2301171394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yegor Gaydar, leader of the Russia's Choice faction 
in the State Duma, has expressed hope that the new Cabinet of 
Ministers will not do things that will quickly wreck the economy. 
  Speaking at a democratic meeting in Moscow, Yegor Gaydar 
said 
that reformers in the government had seen Russia as a state that 
could serve society. In his words, this approach envisaged 
cutting down the state apparatus and minimizing officials' right 
to divide and distribute; and reformers did achieve some degree 
of success. 
  Yegor Gaydar noted that by the time he left the government, 
the average salary in Russia had reached $100 a month, a large 
trade surplus had been achieved, and large stocks of grain to 
last until the next harvest had been amassed. Hence, dependence 
on grain imports has decreased sharply, the free market is 
beginning to work, and shortages have been fended off. 
  Yegor Gaydar said that if the situation becomes critical, 
members of the present government might try to lay the blame for 
it on the reformers. 
  He declined to comment on reports that Mikhail Gorbachev's 
former consultants, Leonid Abalkin and Nikolay Petrakov, have 
been drafted in to adjust the economic reform. 

</TEXT>

