<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Comments Before Departing for China </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401203594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1909 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401203594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev does not 
intend to take a "pro-Serbian" position in the settlement of the 
Bosnian conflict despite the threats from LDP [Liberal 
Democratic Party] leader Vladimir Zhirinovskiy. Kozyrev 
announced this to an Interfax correspondent before leaving 
Moscow for Kyrgyzstan and China on Monday. 
  Zhirinovskiy stated last week that he gave Kozyrev a "week 
for thought," and if the Russian foreign minister did not 
correct his approach Zhirinovskiy would seek his resignation. 
  The foreign minister pointed out that the LDP leader's 
position was an "overt attempt to push Russia into a world war." 
He warned against engaging Russia in the conflict on the Balkan 
peninsula, where the First World War had started and led to the 
seizure in Russia of power by an irresponsible clique causing 
monstrous damage to the country for 70 years. 
  According to Kozyrev, "some political forces" may try to get 
Russia involved in a "global catastrophe," to make a career of 
this and to seize power. 
  "I am not satisfied with this scenario either in foreign or 
in domestic policy and I will never be satisfied with it. If 
after this Zhirinovskiy demands my resignation I will consider 
this as the best recognition of the correctness of my policy," 
the minister pointed out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

