<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Remarks on Various Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401203094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1909 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401203094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] "I would not be in a hurry to call the new 
composition of the Russian government conservative," Russian 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev told a group of journalists 
before his departure for Kyrgyzstan and China. 
  The minister said he had met with Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin and Prime minister Viktor Chernomyrdin before leaving on 
the visits and called these meetings "rich in content." Kozyrev 
said the prime minister was "determined to maintain financial 
discipline, even restrict it, and limit spending and loans." 
  Kozyrev said Chernomyrdin intended to attend to the European 
Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland, to explain Russia's 
economic policy there. "We are planning considerable steps to 
streamline the economic reforms," he pointed out. 
  The foreign minister said he believed it a big mistake of 
Moscow's western partners and friends to wait for the failure of 
reforms in Russia. "It is necessary to make real business and 
help the Russian reforms instead of waiting for the scenario of 
the end of the world to come," he said. 
  In an answer to an Interfax question, Kozyrev said his 
political views had seen no changes. 
  "Kozyrev is still the same," the minister said. "He still 
supports good-neighborly relations with the Baltic states and an 
organized withdrawal of (Russian - IF note) troops on the basis 
of agreements rather than cries about occupants, etc., what I 
call political hysteria. But he still supports observing human 
rights." At the same time, Kozyrev regretted that the Baltic 
states "were going further along the way of violating human 
rights." Among such violations, the minister indicated the 
"attempt to deport dozens of thousands people" from Latvia and 
"possibly Estonia." 

</TEXT>

