<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   China Listed as High Priority in Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401142394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1402 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Georgiy Shmelev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 24 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin's historic, "breakthrough" trip to China has brought the 
two countries to more dynamic partnership on the international 
scene and in bilateral relations. China is a high-priority 
country in Russia's foreign policy, declared Deputy Foreign 
Minister of Russia Aleksandr Panov in an interview with 
ITAR-TASS on Monday. 
  The deputy minister said the relationship between the two 
countries should be stripped of all "sensationalism, and should 
just be normal relations between normal neighbors, two 
superpowers" who are cooperating in the interests of each other, 
their region, and the whole world. 
  According to Panov, the fact that the new year is beginning 
with visits by United States President Bill Clinton to Moscow 
and Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev to China is 
symbolic. Although the delegations are in "different weight 
categories", they reinforce the balance which Russia is 
maintaining in its foreign policy, which is directed towards the 
east as much as it is towards the west. 
  Panov said that Kozyrev's official visit, which is scheduled 
to begin on January 26, will include discussion of preparations 
for a return visit to Moscow by Chinese Premier Jiang Zeming. 
  The potential for Russian-Chinese partnership is great, said 
Panov. In particular, Russia has not paid enough attention to 
China's experience in gradual economic reforms, especially in 
the formation of "special" free economic zones. 
  Talks on the two countries' border are currently being held. 
Panov called "groundless" the allegations sometimes made by 
indvidual Russian statesmen (especially in the Far East), to the 
effect that Russia is making one-sided, unjustifiable 
compromises under Chinese pressure. Whenever the two sides make 
concessions, they are reciprocal, "mutual" concessions. 
  As far as the military sphere is concerned, Russia and China 
are negotiating on the withdrawal of some armed forces from the 
border areas. But these withdrawals would not be of a "sharp or 
sensational nature, since it is more and more obvious that no 
military preparations are being made along the border, which is 
becoming a border of friendship", Panov explained. 
  The deputy foreign minister declared that Russian-Chinese 
trade is mutually profitable and does not infringe upon Russia's 
economic interests. This trade will be continually expanded, he 
said. 
  Panov appealed for more complete information on the two 
countries' relations to be made available to society. Kozyrev's 
january visit to Beijing is destined to play an important role 
in fulfilling this goal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-57175 </DOCNO>
