<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Troop Deployment Prompted by Anonymous Phone Call </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2101201994 Minsk Radio Minsk Network in Belarusian 1815 
GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS2101201994 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk Radio Minsk Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Belarusian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Let us go back to a report by Ivan Gerasyuk and the 
explanation by Stanislav Shushkevich, who proposed to hear Major 
General Konstantin Platonov, deputy interior minister and the 
commander of Interior Ministry troops, today at a 
behind-closed-doors meeting. In spite of the proposal, 
Konstantin Platonov gave no official response. 
  Here is what Deputy Aleksandr Lukashenko, who had a phone 
conversation with Konstantin Platonov, told a BELINFORM 
correspondent. The general said that he received an anonymous 
phone call on Thursday [20 January]. An identified person 
threatened to apply terrorist acts against people's deputies if 
Interior Minister Vladimir Yegorov and KGB Chief Eduard 
Shirkovskiy did not resign. This is the reason Konstantin 
Platonov assumed responsibility and issued an order to put an 
Interior Ministry detachment on alert and move it, unarmed, 
closer to the Government House. When the call proved to be a 
hoax, the detachment was sent back to its permanent quarters. 
  Thus, the presence of an Interior Ministry battalion near 
the 
Music Comedy Theater is a true fact. However, there is still no 
official version on the incident. 
  There remain questions instead: Why was such an important 
decision adopted at the level of deputy minister? Why were 
Stanislav Shushkevich, head of the Security Council, and other 
decisionmaking officials, such as the interior minister and the 
KGB chief, not informed about the threat hanging over the 
deputies? 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

