<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Duma Discusses Reinstituting TV Program, Media </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101205894 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1900 GMT 
21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2101205894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The State Duma has gone into recess until 1 
February. Today, a day of work, the deputies finished forming 
the parliamentary committees. [passage omitted] 
  They also discussed resuming televising of the Parliamentary 
Hour program. Mikhail Poltoranin, chairman of the Committee on 
Information Policy and Communications, stated that the campaign 
against the State Duma in the mass media is an echo of the war 
which was waged between the fourth estate and the former Russian 
Federation parliament. In order to break this tendency, a 
number of measures must be carried out, the chairman said. In 
particular, a State Duma press center must be set up through 
which objective information could be fed to newspapers, radio, 
and television. 
  As for the Parliamentary Hour television broadcast, the 
committee thinks it would be pointless to have this in the form 
in which it emerged under the former Supreme Soviet. Many 
deputies disputed this stance, however, and as a result they 
made no decision on the matter. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-57198 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov015_b_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-015 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fedorov Receives Offer To Remain Finance Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2301225294 Moscow Radio Moscow World Service in English 
2200 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2301225294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Russian Finance Minister Boris Fedorov, who said 
last week that he was going to resign, appeared in the TV 
program "Itogi" on Sunday to inform that he met Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin and got an offer to remain in office. Mr. 
Fedorov said he intended to meet President Yeltsin early this 
week to make a final decision. Boris Fedorov advanced as a 
condition for his continued service for the government the 
resignation of Vice Premier Aleksandr Zaveryukha, who is 
responsible for the agricultural sector, and the Chairman of the 
Central Bank Viktor Gerashchenko. For Boris Fedorov, these two 
are a symbol of anti-reformist trends in the government. 

</TEXT>

