<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Says Fedorov Still Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401115794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1115 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401115794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 24 TASS -- Russian Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin denied that he had contradicted with the 
president over the new government composition and said Boris 
Fedorov remains the finance minister for the time being. 
  "There are no and will be no contradictions" with Boris 
Yeltsin. "I have never put my problems on the shoulders of the 
president and I am not going to do that", Chernomyrdin told 
reporters on Monday after a 30-minute meeting with the 
president, adding that the talks focused on the 1994 budget. 
  Boris Fedorov remains the finance minister for the time 
being 
and it is the president who is to decide on his fate, according 
to the prime minister. 
  "Fedorov continues to work in his position. I have not 
accepted his resignation", Chernomyrdin said adding that it is 
the president who is to decide on whether to accept Fedorov's 
resignation. 
  "I do not know whether he will do it", Chernomyrdin said. 
  The prime minister denied press reports that economist 
Leonid 
Abalkin was appointed his adviser. Abalkin was responsible for 
economic reform in the government of former Soviet Prime 
Minister Nikolay Ryzhkov. 
  On Monday Chernomyrdin left for the city of Orel in central 
Russia where he is to meet 18 regional leaders to discuss the 
situation in agriculture. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

