<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gaydar Discusses Ruble-Dollar Exchange Rate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401102694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0956 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401102694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By BUSINESS-TASS correspondent Robert Serebrennikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 24 TASS -- "Abrupt jumps of the 
dollar exchange rate against the ruble on the Russian currency 
market last week were due to the uncertainty about the 
government's policy," Russia's Choice leader Yegor Gaydar said 
in an exclusive interview today. 
  Gaydar said the present exchange rate is being artificially 
maintained in the country. 
  "In December the Central Bank of Russia intervened with its 
own currency resources to prevent the ruble from plummeting," 
Gaydar said. "The main factor which determined the favourable 
dynamics of the ruble exchange rate consisted in a combination 
of high interest rates against the low pace of the money mass 
growth and relatively low inflationary anticipation," he said. 
  One component of this situation is no longer there since the 
inflation anticipation has skyrocketed. "If the second component 
-- the low pace of the money mass growth -- collapses, the 
dollar exchange rate will keep jumping from time to time," 
Gaydar said. But if the government departs from a tough credit 
and monetary policy, the drop in the ruble exchange rate can 
become a dramatic long-term factor of the Russian economy, he 
said. 
  "I think one should be very prudent about attempts at 
maintaining the ruble exchange rate by copious currency 
interventions," Gaydar said. "It was very hard for us accumulate 
official state reserves starting from scratch in 1992 to 4.5 
billion dollars. It would be too dangerous and irresponsible to 
squander them within a few days," Gaydar warned. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

