<H3> <TI>   Interior Minister Resigns After Lithuanians' Arrest </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401172794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1703 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401172794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Urgent" report by BELINFORM correspondent for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Minsk January 24 TASS -- Belarusian Interior 
Minister Vladimir Yegorov resigned on Monday ceding to the 
pressure of the hard-line parliament. 
  Lawmakers' indignation was caused by a scandalous arrest in 
the Belarusian capital Minsk on January 15 of two leaders of the 
banned Communist Party of Lithuania, Mykolas Burokevicius and 
Jozas Jarmalavicius, who were on a wanted list in their republic 
and their further extradiction from Belarus. 
  Another scandal followed when interior troops were sent 
close 
to the building where the parliamentary session was considering 
whether the arrest was legal. Lawmaker Ivan Gerasyuk asked the 
parliament to clear up on whose orders the troops arrived and 
lawmakers demanded to sack the interior minister and the KGB 
chief. 
  The government has adopted the minister's resignation and 
decided to inform the parliament on the matter. 

</TEXT>

