<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Parliament Session </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101173494 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1450 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2101173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev -- Volodymyr Pryadko, chairman of the board of 
the State Property Fund of Ukraine, reported at the plenary 
session of the Supreme Council of Ukraine on 21 January that in 
accordance with the draft state privatization program, there are 
plans to privatize 20,000 facilities of unfinished construction 
and 8,000 medium and large enterprises in 1994. It is 
envisioned that as a result of implementing the proposed 
program, the share of the non-state sector in the economy will 
come to 28 percent and that the state will receive over 21 
trillion karbovantsi and approximately $230 million. Delivering 
a report, Volodymyr Pylypchuk, chairman of the Supreme Council 
commission for issues of economic reform and management of the 
national economy, mentioned 11 observations regarding the draft 
of the said program, and stressed the necessity of applying 
administrative penalties to officials who disregard the 
privatization process. After Supreme Council commissions have 
elaborated the draft, taking into account proposals expressed by 
people's deputies during the discussion, it will be resubmitted 
for hearings during the next plenary cycle of sessions. 
  A law "On the procedure for leaving and entering Ukraine for 
citizens of Ukraine" was adopted. It envisions simplification 
of the procedure for formalizing exit documents. Speaker 
Valentyn Nedryhaylo, first deputy minister of internal affairs 
of Ukraine, replied to questions on the investigation in the 
affair of the disappearance of Mykhaylo Boychyshyn, head of the 
People's Movement of Ukraine [Rukh] secretariat. Four main 
versions of the disappearance are being worked on, additional 
ones have appeared, and Interpol and investigative bodies from 
CIS countries have joined the investigation, but so far, 
according to Valentyn Nedryhaylo, "new signals have not been 
received." A law "On state secrets" was adopted without 
fundamental changes; the law "On data protection in automated 
systems" was approved in its first reading, and the Forestry 
Code of Ukraine, which was adopted, will come into force from 
the day of publication. 
  The next plenary session of the Supreme Council will take 
place on 25 January. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

