<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Arrives on Working Visit, Met by Akayev </TI></H3>
<H4>   Holds Talks With Akayev </H4>
<F P=102> LD2501084394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0822 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501084394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Boris Maynayev and Georgiy </F>
Shmelev] 
  [Text] Bishkek January 25 TASS -- Kyrgyzstan feels no 
Russian imperial ambitions and will work to ensure that ethnic 
Russians do not emigrate from the Central Asian republic, 
according to President of Kyrgyzstan Askar Akayev. 
  Kyrgyzstan "sees no imperial ambitions in Russian actions 
and 
does not feel any pressure from Moscow", he told a press 
conference after meeting Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev 
on Tuesday and added that he intends to use every effort to 
strengthen the provisions fixed in the Russian-Kyrgyz friendship 
treaty. 
  Akayev also stressed that he would do everything possible so 
that nealy a million of Russian ethnics living in Kyrgyzstan "do 
not feel any inconveniences" and that the Central Asian republic 
"remains good motherland for all citizens of the country, 
including Russians". 
  Kozyrev, in his turn, said the Russian leadership supports 
democratic Kyrgyzstan and will render any necessary assistance 
to President Akayev. 
  The minister added that the protection of the rights of 
Russians in CIS countries has nothing in common with imperial 
ambitions. Human rights protection has nothing in common with 
"imperial policy as Russia respected and respects sovereign 
rights of its equal partners", Kozyrev said. 
  He handed over to Akayev a message from Boris Yeltsin in 
which the Russian president pledged support to market reforms 
and democratic transformations of Kyrgyz authorities. 
  Akayev and Kozyrev signed a consular convention and a 
protocol on the exchange of ratification credentials to the 
treaty "on legal assistance and legal relations in civil, family 
and criminal cases". 
  Kozyrev, who is accompanied by Deputy Defence Minister Boris 
Gromov, left for the city of Blagoveshchensk on the border with 
China from where he will proceed for a visit to the neighbouring 
country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-57244 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov016_l_94004" </HT>


