<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Arrives on Working Visit, Met by Akayev </TI></H3>
<H4>   Apologizes for `Fascist Statements' </H4>
<F P=102> LD2501114594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1111 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501114594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia's foreign policy has not undergone any 
changes, Russian Minister Andrey Kozyrev told Kyrgyz President 
Askar Akayev on Tuesday. 
  Kozyrev said that neither the patriots, nor the fascists 
influence Russian foreign policy in any way. However, he 
apologized for the "fascist statements made in Moscow recently." 
The protection of ethnic Russians in the former Soviet 
republics has nothing to do with imperialism, he continued. He 
emphasized, though, that "we cannot remain indifferent to 
violations of ethnic Russians' rights, particularly in Latvia, 
from where they are being forced out." 
  Akayev said that he did not see any imperial ambitions in 
Russia's foreign policy. "Without a strong and great Russia, 
stability in Eurasia is unthinkable," he said. Speaking about 
the problem of dual citizenship, he noted that it should be 
tackled on a bilateral basis. 
  Kozyrev announced that Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin was to arrive in Bishkek shortly for comprehensive 
talks on economic cooperation. 

</TEXT>

