<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Factions Jointly Prepare Citizenship Draft Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401201694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1909 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401201694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The nationalist factions "Movement for Latvia's 
National Independence" and "Fatherland and Freedom" of the 
Latvian Saeima (parliament) today jointly prepared a draft law 
on citizenship to be submitted for referendum. 
  According to the draft law, Latvian citizenship could be 
granted only to ethnic Latvians who have returned to the 
republic; those legally residing in Latvia before 1940 but 
lacking citizenship; spouses of Latvian citizens living on the 
Latvian territory over 10 years and citizens of Lithuania and 
Estonia permanently residing in the republic. 
  In addition, the factions proposed setting the annual quotas 
for granting citizenship at 0.1% of the Latvian population. At 
the moment, it is about 1900 persons a year. 
  The authors of the draft law propose the beginning of the 
naturalization be linked with the ultimate withdrawal of Russian 
troops. 
  At a press conference, they pointed out that their proposals 
were an alternative to the document prepared by the ruling 
coalition, encompassing the factions "Latvian Way" and 
"Peasants' Union," which was passed in the first reading last 
December. 
  This draft law stipulates that the Latvian citizenship could 
be granted to former citizens of the Soviet Union permanently 
residing in Latvia for over 10 years and having command of the 
Latvian language. The annual naturalization quota will be set 
by the republican government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-57250 </DOCNO>
