<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Only Citizens Can Be Informers for Security </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2401104794 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 22 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM2401104794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Irina Litvinova report: "Only Latvian `Citizens' Have </F>
Right To Spy"] 
  [Text] Riga -- The Latvian Seimas has adopted a "law on 
operational activity," whole sections of which provide broad 
scope for the special services. Correspondence can be monitored 
and secretly copied, conversations can be bugged, and people can 
be followed. 
  Operational activity relies on "cooperation with the 
population." Those who used to be called "informers" are now 
known as "secret assistants." Here too there was no getting 
away from the division between the rights of Latvian "citizens" 
and "noncitizens" (who comprise one-third of the population). 
Only "citizens" can collect information on other persons, 
facts, and cases -- in other words, become "secret assistants." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

