<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Changes in G-24 Credits' Distribution Sought </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2401152794 Tallinn BNS in English 1338 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2401152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jan 24, BNS -- The Foreign Assistance 
Coordination Commission looked through proposals to change the 
procedure of distributing G-24 credits in Latvia, Finance 
Ministry's spokesman Valdis Freidenfelds told BNS. 
  In the commission's opinion, contracts on the delivery of 
equipment, raw materials or fuel should be paid through 
banks-distributors of the credit. 
  Recipients should directly receive no more than 15 percent 
of 
the total worth of a credit, the commission said. The 
regulation is designed to prevent financial machinations with 
credit money. 
  The group also reviewed the Indication Program, which is 
implemented in the framework of the PHARE [Poland and Hungary 
for Restructuring the Economy] program. In 1994, the program's 
funding will be used to finance economic, administrative and 
agricultural reforms. 
  The 1994 PHARE action mainstreams will be adopted in March 
in 
Brussels. Latvia could receive an estimated 21 million ECU's, 
specialists say. 
  The commission is headed by Finance Minister Uldis Osis, its 
members are Economics Minister Ojars Kehris, Economics 
Ministry's State Secretary Aina Bataraga and Bank of Latvia's 
Vice President Ilmars Rimasevics. It was set up in the end of 
1993 in compliance with a government resolution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

