<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Slump in Farm Production in 1993 Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2401121394 Tallinn BNS in English 1729 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2401121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jan 22, BNS -- The output of farm produce 
decreased 16 percent compared with last year, the Latvian State 
Statistics Committee reports. 
  From this, plant growing dropped 5 percent and 
cattlebreeding 
declined 22 percent. 
  The production of grain and sugar beet reduced 18 percent 
and 
30 percent, respectively, over the last two years. 
  The total yield of potatoes and vegetables, however, is on 
the rise. It increased for at least one-third because of the 
expanding areas sown with these crops. 
  Farmers owned 90 percent (71 percent in 1991) potato 
planting 
areas and 95 percent (65 percent in 1991) vegetable sowing and 
planting areas. 
  The total amount of meat produced in 1993 was 281,000 tons, 
or 76 percent, the total amount of milk was 1,219,000, or 82 
percent, the total amount of eggs 387,000,000, or 65 percent, 
compared with 1992. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

