<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Seeks To Disband National Assembly </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401192094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1642 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401192094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" No. 15 feature] </F>
  [Text] The Azeri parliament is still to give its assessment 
of the January 1990 tragedy in Baku. Last Friday the opposition 
deputies blocked again the parliament's decision on the issue. 
Opposition deputies believe that only a new, democratically 
elected parliament is able to evaluate the events of three years 
ago when over 100 Baku residents died. 
  The leader of the National Independence Party Etibar Mamedov 
and representatives of the People's Front of Azerbaijan believe 
that the present parliament formed under ex-president Ayaz 
Mutalibov demonstrated more than once its unprincipled approach 
and took decisions to please each leadership. The Front's 
faction demands the disbandment of parliament and the holding of 
new elections. 
  The opposition disagrees with the point of view of President 
Geydar Aliyev and other leaders who are convinced that the 
former First Secretary of the Azeri Communist Party Central 
Committee Abdurakhman Vezirov, the then Chairman of the 
republic's Council of Ministers A. Mutalibov and the then KGB 
Chairman Vagif Guseynov are to bear responsibility for what 
happened January 20, 1990. The deputies of the People's Front 
of Azerbaijan and of the Party for National Independence believe 
that the political leadership of the former Soviet Union who 
took the decision to bring in troops in Baku are the main 
culprits of the tragedy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

