<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Funds on Hand for Setting Up Internment Camp </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2401111794 Tallinn BNS in English 1255 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2401111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 22, BNS -- Estonia at the moment has 
no funds available for building an internment camp for illegal 
immigrants, said the Minister of Justice Kaido Kama. 
  Kama told BNS today that construction and repair work on the 
facilities of a former prison guards' military unit base at 
Rummu would cost about 20 million kroons. 
  The project currently is in its initial stages. 
  "The Police Department says the camp must be designed for at 
least 500 persons," the minister said. He said it was still not 
clear whether the camp really needed to be as large as this. 
  The government on Sept. 14 ruled that the internment camp 
was to be located at Rummu, some 35 km to the southwest of 
Tallinn. Other possible locations discussed before that date 
included a former Soviet Army disciplinary correction unit camp 
at Paldiski, the Harku detention camp on the outskirts of 
Tallinn, and a former Communist Pioneer youth organization camp 
near the Tallinn. 

</TEXT>

