<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fate of Kurdish Refugees `Unclear' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2401205694 Tallinn ETA NEWS RELEASE in English 1758 GMT 24 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS2401205694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA NEWS RELEASE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The future of Kurdish refugees in Estonia remains 
unclear as they have no documents and no country is willing to 
accept them, Valeri Kravets, deputy director of the National 
Board of Corrections, said in an interview with ETA. 
  At present, 35 Kurdish refugees, nine of them children and 
11 
women, stay at Harku prison near Tallinn, Kravets said. None of 
them holds any document, let alone visas, Kravets said while 
adding they had arrived in Estonia illegally from either Russia 
or Latvia, but Estonia could not send them back without 
documents. 
  The number of Kurdish refugees was the biggest in September 
(63), Kravets said. Those who had money and connections left 
for Sweden while others just sit and wait, he added. 
  No solution is near, Kravets said. Finland has hinted at 
accepting them, but no formal promises have been made, Kravets 
said. 
  In addition to above-mentioned refugees who had arrived in 
Estonia earlier, three Kurds had been detained at the Port of 
Tallinn on an attempt to board a ship to Sweden, Kravets said. 

</TEXT>

