<H3> <TI>   Ambassador Welcomes Yeltsin's Upcoming Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401195994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1816 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401195994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Taranov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 24 TASS -- A high-ranking Georgian 
official welcomed the upcoming signing of the friendship treaty 
between Russia and Georgia as an event of paramount importance 
for Georgia. 
  "The treaty of friendship, good neighbourly relations and 
cooperation between the Russian Federation and the Republic of 
Georgia which is expected to be signed during the first official 
visit to Georgia by the Russian president on February 3-4 will 
be epoch-making for Georgia," Georgian Ambassador to Russia 
Valeryan Advadze said. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS on Monday, Advadze said "we 
have gone a long way while preparing the treaty. We have 
overcome many obstacles on our way. But today we are on the 
last lap. This has become possible due to the efforts of 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Georgian leader Eduard 
Shevardnadze." 
  He stressed that Yeltsin's visit to independent Georgia will 
signify that "it has been recognised by the great neighbour." 
"The upcoming visit of the Russian president to Georgia will 
help restore human relations between the people of the two 
countries," the ambassador said. 
  During the visit, the two leaders also plan to sign 
agreements on trade and economic cooperation, on the status of 
Russian border troops in Georgia, on cooperation in 
transportation, on the resettlement of refugees and other 
documents. 

</TEXT>

