<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abkhaz Deputy Responds to Council Chairman </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401221394 Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network in Georgian 1900 
GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2401221394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Georgian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Abkhazia's mass media reports that Vladislav 
Ardzinba, chairman of Abkhazia's Supreme Council, in an 
interview with Abkhaz television said that only those Georgian 
refugees who had not participated in the war and had not shed 
blood in Abkhazia could return to Abkhazia. 
  A SAKINFORM [Georgian press agency] correspondent, Tengiz 
Pachkoria, asked Akaki Gasviani, deputy chairman of Abkhazia's 
Council of Ministers, to comment on this statement. 
  Gasviani said: We consider Ardzinba's statement to reflect 
an attempt to revise and reconsider the Geneva agreement 
envisaging the return of all refugees. Ardzinba and his 
supporters, who on several occasions violated the Sochi 
agreement on settling the Abkhaz conflict peacefully, are now 
trying to violate the Geneva agreements and the communique. 
Obviously, the return of dozens of thousands of refugees to the 
Gali and Abkhazia's other rayons is not suitable for them. This 
statement by Ardzinba is a fresh attempt at holding the Georgian 
population and the Georgian Government responsible for the 
actions committed by the Abkhaz and the north Caucasian 
combatants who had killed and pillaged the civilian population 
of the autonomous republic--Georgians, Russians, Greeks, and 
others--and for the combatants' actions--bombing and shelling 
residential areas of Sukhumi and Abkhazia's other towns and 
rayons. As for the criminal offenses committed in Abkhazia in 
1992-93, we must investigate thoroughly these instances, and 
criminal proceedings must be instituted against perpetrators 
irrespective of their nationality. 

</TEXT>

