<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leader Denounced for Barring Georgian Refugees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401155994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1520 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401155994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tengiz Pachkoriya] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi January 24 TASS -- A Georgian top official 
has denounced Abkhazian leader Vladislav Ardzinba for his 
statement barring Georgian refugees who fought on the side of 
Georgian troops from returning to Abkhazia. 
  Ardzinba told Abkhazian television that only those Georgian 
refugees who have not "stained themselves with blood" may return 
to Abkhazia. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS on Monday, Akaky Gasviani, a 
vice- prime minister of the Georgian government-in-exile of 
Abkhazia, described Ardzinba's statement as "an attempt to 
revise and reconsider the Geneva agreements envisaging the 
return to Abkhazia of refugees of all nationalities irrespective 
of their participation in combat activities." 
  He said the Abkhazian leadership "is obviously not happy 
about the return of several dozen thousand refugees to the Gali 
and other districts of Abkhazia and it is trying, under various 
pretexts, to obstruct the process of their return." 
  Gasviani stressed that Ardzinba's statement "is a new 
attempt 
to shift the responsibility for the activities of Abkhazian and 
North Caucasian militants who robbed and killed civilians in 
Abkhazia -- Georgians, Russians, Greeks and people of other 
nationalities -- in September-December 1993 to the Georgian 
population and Georgian authorities." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

