<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy Says Date for Armenian-Azerbaijani Summit Not Set </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401165194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1520 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401165194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: by correspondents </F>
Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and 
others] 
  [Text] A concrete date for the possible meeting between 
Azeri President Gaydar Aliyev and his Armenian counterpart Levon 
Ter-Petrosyan in Moscow has not been fixed yet, the special 
envoy of President Yeltsin, Vladimir Kazimirov, who leads 
Russia's mission for settling the conflict in Karabakh, told 
INTERFAX on Monday [24 January]. 
  "Meetings on such a level should be prepared very 
carefully," 
he pointed out. "It's premature to mention concrete dates 
before concluding preparations that would ensure success for the 
proposed summit," he said. 
  According to Kazimirov, Russian mediators intend to continue 
the work they are conducting "in the three major points of the 
conflict" -- Baku, Yerevan, and Stepanakert, as well as in 
Moscow. "As long as we are at this stage, I am not in a 
position to say when this work can be raised to a higher level," 
the diplomat said. 
  The meetings held in Moscow recently by Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev with his Azeri and Armenian counterparts 
Gasan Gasanov and Vagan Papazian, as well as with a spokesman 
for the leadership of Nagorno-Karabakh, Arkadiy Gukasyan, showed 
that "the stands taken by the conflicting sides drew somewhat 
closer," he noted. 
  Nevertheless, the talks were "rather complicated," Kazimirov 
said. "We are dealing with one of the fiercest and longest 
conflicts in the territory of the former USSR. Therefore it 
would be naive to believe that the entire knot of problems will 
be untangled to the satisfaction of all the parties concerned 
overnight. We proceed from the assumption that a settlement 
will be gradual, that it will consist of searches for 
compromises on virtually all points," the diplomat said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

