<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Mercenaries' Said Fighting in Karabakh Conflict </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2101202294 Tallinn BNS in English 1632 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2101202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 21, BNS -- Mercenaries from Estonia and 
Lithuania fight as part of the Armenian troops in the conflict 
over the Nagorno-Karabakh region, said a Russian soldier taken 
prisoner by Azerbaijani forces in December. 
  A BNS correspondent has seen videotapes of the interrogation 
of the Russian soldier, Vasily Lugovoy, by Azerbaijani Interior 
Minister Vagif Novruzov. 
  Lugovoy at interrogations in the Azerbaijani capital Baku on 
Jan. 15 said he had met three female snipers near the 
Juhhar-Bahmal village in the conflict region on Dec. 28 and 29. 
  The three woman soldiers had claimed they were from the 
Baltics. Lugovoy says the women had talked with what he called a 
Baltic accent and were either Lithuanians or Estonians. 
  Lugovoy, a former Soviet military, served as mercenary in a 
pioneer unit of the Armenian troops. He said he had also 
previously met both male and female wage soldiers from Estonia 
and Lithuania. He said the Armenians valued highly the skills of 
"mercenaries from the Baltics" and paid them in U.S. dollars. 
Lugovoy said Russian soldiers earned 35,000 rubles a day in the 
Karabakh fighting in late 1993. 
  The Russian soldier also said in the interrogation he had 
been told that "two Baltic mercenaries" were granted the rank of 
senior lieutenant of the Armenian Armed Forces and that they had 
received a personal gun as gift from Armenia. 
  Lugovoy, born in 1960, formerly served in the Soviet troops 
in Germany. 
  A BNS correspondent earlier has met with an artillery 
officer 
fighting on the Armenian side in Nagorno-Karabakh, who said he 
came from Estonia. The man, however, was not ethnic Estonian. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

