<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baltic States Council Appoints Human Rights Commissioner </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2101212794 Tallinn BNS in English 1932 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2101212794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 21, BNS -- The Senior Officials 
Committee of the Council of the Baltic Sea States adopted a 
budget for the institution of the council's Commissioner for 
Human Rights and Ethnic Minority Issues and discussed possible 
nominations for the office. 
  The Senior Officials Committee met in Tallinn on Jan. 20-21. 
  A final decision on establishing the new commissioner's 
institution with the Council of the Baltic Sea States must be 
made by the council's foreign ministers at conference to be held 
in Tallinn in May, said Mare Kukk, the head of the Estonian 
coordination bureau of the council. 
  Kukk said the new office was designed as an expert 
institution to consult the council's member countries, 
coordinate the activities of human rights organizations and 
inform the international community about the human rights and 
minority rights situation in region. 
  The commissioner will not engage in resolving conflicts, 
Kukk 
added. 
  The draft of the commissioner's mandate was approved by the 
senior officials in September. 
  The budget of the new office, established at about 270,000 
German marks, is much smaller than that of the CSCE High 
Commissioner for Human Rights and Ethnic Minorities. Expenses 
will be covered proportionally by all members of the council 
according to the size of the country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

