<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechen Official on Talks With Chernomyrdin on Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401210294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1909 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401210294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Among other issues, the Russian and Chechen sides 
discussed the possibility of a meeting between Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin and Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev at the 
bilateral talks in Moscow last week, Chechen Prime Minister 
Mairbek Mugadayev [title as received] told a press conference in 
Groznyy today. 
  He said his two-hour meeting with Russian Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin focused on a wide range of issues related to 
the concluding of a treaty on the principles for economic 
cooperation between Russia and the Chechen Republic. The 
Chechen official pointed out that "all the issues the Chechen 
delegation raised before the Russian prime minister were 
understood and approved. The two sides came to the conclusion 
that a political settlement and a meeting of the heads of state 
were needed for the resolution of all economic disputes." 
  "In turn, V.Chernomyrdin hoped that such a meeting could be 
held in the near future," Mugadayev said. 
  The Chechen prime minister said the meeting touched on the 
possibility of freeing the former speaker of the Russian Supreme 
Soviet, Chechen citizen Ruslan Khasbulatov accused of organizing 
the armed uprising in Moscow in early October. 

</TEXT>

