<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baltic UN Envoys Present Statement on Kozyrev Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2501165894 Tallinn BNS in English 1414 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2501165894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 25, BNS -- The permanent 
representatives of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania in the United 
Nations today handed over to the U.N. Secretary-General 
Butrus-Ghali a joint Baltic statement on the remarks made on 
Jan. 18 by Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev. 
  The Russian minister, speaking to his country's ambassadors 
in Moscow, declared Russia's "vital interest" in the territory 
of the former Soviet Union and said Russia must not withdraw its 
troops from the former republics. 
  A letter sent with today's statement by the three Baltic 
countries requests that the statement be circulated as a U.N. 
official document under the "Complete Withdrawal of Foreign 
Troops from the Territories of the Baltic States" topic of the 
General Assembly's agenda, as well as in the U.N. Security 
Council, a representative at the Estonian Foreign Ministry said. 

</TEXT>

