<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Program for Kozyrev PRC Visit Previewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2601101794 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 26 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2601101794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report: "Russian-Chinese Talks in Beijing"] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 26 Jan -- Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev arrives in Beijing Wednesday on a four-day official 
visit. This trip, which is regarded here as an important event 
in rapidly progressing Chinese-Russian relations, is being made 
in line with the accords reached during Russian Federation 
President Boris Yeltsin's visit to the PRC in December 1992. 
  The head of Russia's foreign policy department will hold 
talks with his Chinese counterpartue Qian Qichen and will meet 
with Jiang Z emin, president of the PRC and general secretary of 
the CPC Central Committee, and with Li Peng, premier of the PRC 
State Council. One of the main topics to be discussed by the 
sides is the preparation of the second top-level Russian-Chinese 
meeting, this time in Moscow. 
  The sides will examine regional and international problems 
of 
interest to Russia and China as permanent members of the UN 
Security Council. It is believed here that the situation in 
Northeast Asia, where the nuclear problem of the Korean 
Peninsula is most acute, also will not be overlooked. 
  Key aspects of bilateral relations -- trade-economic and 
military-technical cooperation and border questions -- will be 
touched on during the talks between Andrey Kozyrev and Qian 
Qichen, which are being held within the framework of regular 
consultations between the two countries' Foreign Ministries. 
  The talks are expected to result in the signing of an 
intergovernmental agreement on crossing points on the 
Russian-Chinese border and also a protocol on consultations 
between the Russian Federation and PRC Foreign Ministries. 
  The Russian minister will address Chinese political experts 
at the Institute of People's Diplomacy in Beijing and will visit 
the Shenzhen special economic zone in the south of the country, 
which is an experimental base in implementing reform and a 
policy of openness. He will also visit the ancient capital of 
the Middle State -- the city of Xian, the cradle of Chinese 
civilization. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

