<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   North Ossetians Oppose Additional Russian Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK2601103094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 26 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK2601103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Natalya Gorodetskaya report under the "Conflict" rubric: </F>
"North Ossetia Against Bringing Additional Russian Troops. 
State of Emergency Regime Will Apparently Be Extended"] 
  [Text] Vyacheslav Titorenko, representative of the Russian 
Federation Government interdepartmental commission for the 
elimination of the aftermath of the Ossetia-Ingushetia conflict, 
has arrived in North Ossetia, in the zone under the emergency 
situation regime. According to INTERFAX, the purpose of his 
arrival is to coordinate the actions of all interested 
ministries and agencies, including "power" ministries and 
agencies, to implement the Russian Federation president's edict 
on returning to their homes refugees and those who have been 
forced to resettle. 
  In the meantime, there is growing dissatisfaction in the 
republic at an alleged introduction of additional Russian 
military formations onto its territory. The All-Ossetia 
"Greater Council" ("Styr Nykhas") and the pan-national movement 
"Our Ossetia" have passed a request to Russian Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin to confirm or deny this information. A 
statement circulated by these movements says that on the 
territory of North Ossetia now "there are more than enough 
military formations to ensure security in the zone affected by 
the emergency situation regime." In the view of the statement's 
authors, troops are being brought in the republic in order "to 
create a powerful military fist in the center of the Caucasus," 
capable of "pacifying" the Caucasian peoples." North Ossetia's 
public movements have demanded that the Russian Government 
withdraw the additional troops from the republic's territory, 
and discontinue support to extremist circles in Georgia's 
leadership. 
  It appears that the possible introduction of additional 
Russian troops is causing such dissatisfaction because the 
emergency situation regime is to end on 31 January. On 28 
January, North Ossetia's parliament intends to discuss this 
question, and, according to information from Vladikavkaz, many 
deputies will speak categorically against extending the validity 
of the emergency situation. However, INTERFAX reports, it is 
known from competent sources that the president of North Ossetia 
is now ready to sign an edict extending the state of emergency, 
but that would affect a considerably smaller area. 
  The edict will apparently be signed after Akhsarbek Galazov, 
former chairman of North Ossetia's Supreme Soviet, is sworn in 
as president. The inauguration ceremony has been scheduled for 
26 January. Invitations for the ceremony have been forwarded to 
Russian Federation President Boris Yeltsin, government chairman 
Viktor Chernomyrdin, and to the leaders of both chambers of 
Russia's Federal Assembly. The leaders of the North Caucasus 
republics, krays, and oblasts are also expected to arrive in 
Vladikavkaz for the ceremony. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-57333 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov017_d_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-017 </AU>
