<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Altay Governor Criticizes Reform Course </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK2501144094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 25 Jan 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK2501144094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed NEGA report in the "Russian Federation -- </F>
Altay Kray" column] 
  [Text] On 24 January a briefing took place at the Kray 
administration where Vladimir Rayfikesht, former head of the 
Kray administration, spoke about the motives for his 
resignation. V. Rayfikesht cited personal reasons as the main 
motive but refused to comment on it. Furthermore, he considers 
it impossible for him to continue work at the post of kray 
governor owing to the inconsistent reform course pursed by the 
government. Rayfikesht blamed the latter for the economic 
crisis and the colossal outflow of hard currency funds and raw 
materials from Russia. At the same time, Rayfikesht stressed 
that "although the government composition is bad, another would 
have been 100 times worse." In Rayfikesht's opinion, Yeltsin 
can no longer enjoy the entirety of his powers. The former 
governor stressed that the Russian president displayed weakness 
when after the elections to the Federal Assembly he failed to 
consolidate the reformist wing in the government. Hence the 
resignation of Gaydar and Fedorov, which only aggravated the 
situation. Summing up his performance in the kray, Rayfikesht 
stated that he is leaving with a clear conscience. First, the 
kray has not become "a preserve of socialism." Second, market 
structures have been put in place. Rayfikesht stressed that the 
incumbent administration is not responsible for the production 
decline in the kray, since that was largely conditioned by the 
financial and credit policy pursued by the government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

