<H3> <TI>   Aliyev Urges Armenia to Withdraw Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501204594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1645 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501204594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature] </F>
  [Text] President Geydar Aliyev says the Azeri army is 
setting an example of heroism reviving the nation's confidence, 
respect and love for its defenders. Speaking during a visit to 
an army unit on Monday, he said there was a revival of patriotic 
feelings in the nation and that latest developments indicated 
the ability by the Azeris and their army to defend their own 
lands." 
  Aliyev spoke of military successes notched up by the army on 
the frontlines of Fizuli, Kelbajar, Agdam and Agderin 
(Mardakert) recently and the nation's pride and joy over those 
achievements. 
  At the same time, the President said that Baku was opposed 
to 
war and still committed to a peaceful solution to the conflict. 
However, the Armenian army continues aggression against 
Azerbaijan by launching new offensives, he said. 
  Aliyev pledged commitment to further efforts for a 
negotiated 
settlement to the conflict saying appropriate contacts were 
under way to this end including Armenia. But he warned against 
further Armenian aggression saying his country would have no 
other option but to recover lost territory by force if that was 
not stopped. 
  The President called on Yerevan to relinquish the occupied 
territories of its own accord, withdraw its troops and respect 
the sovereignty and integrity of Azerbaijan. The war will end 
if the Armenian government fulfils those conditions, Aliyev said. 

</TEXT>

