<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Dismisses Parliamentary Staff Head </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501154894 Tbilisi IBERIA in Georgian 1415 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi IBERIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Georgian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tbilisi, 25 Jan -- An IBERIA correspondent has 
learned that Hamlet Chipashvili, head of the Georgian 
parliamentary staff, has been released from his duties on the 
orders of Eduard Shevardnadze, Georgian head of state. He is 
blamed for failing to promptly make available the full text of 
the Geneva communique to parliamentary members. 
  The parliamentary opposition regards this as the head of 
state's political retaliation against parliamentary vice speaker 
Rusudan Beridze, who oversees the work of the staff. 
  Similar statements were made by the Republicans and Charter 
91, who are Ilya Chavchavadze Association factions. The 
parliamentary majority, in fact, agreed with the decision of the 
head of state and the parliamentary speaker on releasing Hamlet 
Chipashvili from his duties. 

</TEXT>

