<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nazarbayev Interviewed by KAZAKHSTANSKAYA PRAVDA </TI></H3>
<H4>   Optimistic About Future of CIS </H4>
<F P=102> LD2301172694 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1400 GMT 
23 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2301172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kazakhstan President Nursultan Nazarbayev disagrees 
with those who are pessimistic about the future of the CIS. 
  In an interview published in today's KAZAKHSTANSKAYA PRAVDA 
he notes that at the Ashgabat summit the positions of CIS 
countries moved closer together on all matters, notably on 
economic ones. Kazakhstan believes that the economies of CIS 
countries can be stabilized through strengthening the 
integration processes within the framework of the economic 
union, which has now been set up. 
  Nursultan Nazarbayev believes that the introduction of 
individual currencies is a powerful enough impetus for the 
integration of Commonwealth states. He believes that at some 
stage a currency will emerge that will be valid in all CIS 
states. 
  All problems ought to be solved in close cooperation with 
fellow Commonwealth members, and for Kazakhstan that means first 
and foremost with Russia, Nursultan Nazarbayev noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

