<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Concept of Bill `On Political Parties' Criticized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501190294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1627 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501190294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Alexandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 25 TASS -- A concept of the draft 
law "On Political Parties" was criticized today by the majority 
of speakers at hearings of the Russian president's commission 
for legislative proposals. 
  The five-page concept gives the notion of "an all-Russian 
political party", specifies conditions of party formation and 
registration, enumerates party rights and control over party 
activities. 
  The majority of party representatives opposed an idea to 
describe a party as all-Russian only in case of "its support by 
over five per cent of voters in the state Duma elections" and a 
strength of no less than 5,000 members. The commission 
suggested to consider all- Russian only the parties represented 
in the parliament although many of them won the elections within 
larger electoral coalitions. 
  The idea was most severely criticized by parties that did 
not 
gain the five per cent of votes at the recent elections -- the 
Constitutional-Democratic Party, the Conservative Party, the 
Party of Consolidation, the Socialist Party of Working People, 
the National-Republican Party and others. 
  Deputy Russian Labor Minister Vladimir Varov said the 
document is "a worst concept of draft laws discussed by the 
former Supreme Soviet". In his opinion, the body registering a 
party should proceed from party deeds and not its rules or other 
documents which may be written in a way to meet all the 
criteria. "Otherwise, we will soon have dozens of paramilitary 
organizations named `parties'," he stressed. 
  Leader of the Association of Russian Independent 
Professionals Pyotr Filippov called for "application of tougher 
norms to political parties". In his opinion, all parties -- 
including those which exceeded the five per cent limit and those 
which did not -- should constantly confirm their right to 
existence. He said regular re-registration of party members is 
necessary. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-57364 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov017_c_94006" </HT>


