<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Council Postpones Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501210994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1944 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501210994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Ukrainian Supreme Soviet put off a decision on 
the referendum on basic constitutional provisions concerning 
state authorities and local governments at its evening session 
Tuesday [25 January]. 
  Ivan Plyushch, the Supreme Soviet Chairman, told deputies 
that opposing views had crystallized. Numerous deputies want to 
keep the rights of the presidential representatives intact, not 
delegating part of them to the elected bodies. Others insisted 
on electing all local authorities. 
  Plyushch also said that if the Supreme Soviet did not make a 
decision on the referendum, the president had a right to do so. 
  The proposal that a referendum on basic constitutional 
provisions should be held had been made by the constitutional 
conference held on January 14. These provisions include the 
list of the powers to be exercised by the president, the Supreme 
Soviet and the government. 
  By that draft, the president's functions would be only 
representing the country on the international scene and 
supervision of the government activities. 
  The Supreme Soviet would remain the highest legislative body 
while the government would take over all the executive functions. 
  Parliament will continue the debate on January 26. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

