<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rukh Chairman Demands Inquiry Into `Terror' Acts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2501121494 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 22 Jan 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU2501121494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Rukh Believes That a Campaign of </F>
Political Terrorism Is Being Waged Against It"] 
  [Text] On 20 January, the chairman of the Ukraine People's 
Rukh [Movement for Perestroyka] held a news conference during 
which he read the statement, adopted the day before by the Rukh 
central leadership on the terror campaign against Rukh, its 
leaders, and activists. The Rukh believes that the acts of 
terror against it are due to its political line aimed at the 
building of an independent democratic state and at ridding 
Ukraine of the former communist nomenklatura. 
  Vyacheslav Chornovil quoted a number of facts: Several 
attacks, over the recent weeks, on the electoral headquarters of 
the Rukh Chernivtsi regional organization; a pogrom on Christmas 
night in the building of the Ternopil Rukh organization; the 
beating up of the children of several leaders of rayon Rukh 
organizations in Odessa Oblast. Unknown people broke into the 
apartment of the chairman of the Kirovohrad organization, and on 
15 January, there was an attempt to break into the apartment of 
Les Tanyuk, member of the central Rukh leadership and member of 
Ukraine's Supreme Council Presidium. On 17 January, in broad 
daylight, Colonel Serhiy Budko was beaten up in Vinnytsya. 
Finally, there is the attack on the Rukh secretariat in Kiev 
and the disappearance of the head of the secretariat Mykhaylo 
Boychyshyn, of whom nothing is known to this day. 
  Rukh demands that the president and the Supreme Council 
chairman intervene in the situation and that Ukraine's Security 
Service, Ministry of Internal Affairs, and the Procurator 
General's Office investigate the criminal actions against Rukh 
activists. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

