<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNA Terms Rukh Kidnapping `Storm in a Teacup' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2501100794 Lvov POST-POSTUP in Ukrainian 1800 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2501100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Lvov POST-POSTUP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Speaking at a news conference held in Lvov on 24 
January, Andriy Shkil, chairman of the Ukrainian National 
Assembly [UNA] Lvov Oblast Committee, deemed the affair of Rukh 
Deputy Chairman Mykhaylo Boychyshyn's disappearance as a "storm 
in a teacup." Shkil pointed out that "if some people lack 
action, words are brought to the fore, and affairs like this one 
arise." The UNA regional commander underlined: "When Mykhaylo 
Boychyshyn was still Shevchenkivskyy Rayon Council chairman in 
Lvov he had certain connections that could be the motives behind 
his disappearance" and added that "we cannot rule out that in a 
day or two Boychyshyn will emerge safe and sound, and will tell 
tales about his kidnapping." Boychyshyn's wife's televised 
appeal gave this idea to Shkil because "one had the impression 
that she had recently seen her husband." UNA Chairman Yuriy 
Shukhevych said: "Mykhaylo Boychyshyn is not an outstanding Rukh 
activist. Why has there been no similar actions against 
Vyacheslav Chornovil?" The UNA leadership believes that 
Boychyshyn's mysterious disappearance might be linked to Rukh's 
financial activities. 
  Meanwhile, according to a report by Maryana Chorna published 
in Lvov's RATUSHA on 22 January, the newspaper had received 
"unsubstantiated information from law enforcement circles" that 
Mykhaylo Boychyshyn's dead body had been discovered. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

