<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Committee Rejects Call </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2501203294 Tallinn BNS in English 1646 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2501203294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Tallinn, Jan 25, BNS -- The Commission for State 
Defense in the Estonian parliament today ruled to reject a draft 
bill calling for dismissal of the country's commander in chief, 
Major General Aleksander Einseln. The bill was submitted by 
opposition MP Katrin Linde. 
  Peeter Lorents, chairman of the defense commission, said the 
bill was turned down because it contained contradictions with 
the Constitution. Lorents said it was possible that Linde would 
bring the draft in line with legal standards and submit it to 
the parliament for a second time. 
  Lorents added that discussion of the draft had taken place 
in 
a peaceful parliamentary atmosphere. 
  Linde's suggestions were met with irony ranging to taunt at 
Monday's meeting of the parliament. [sentence as received] 
  The draft suggested the dismissal of Aleksander Einseln and 
revoking the earlier law on his appointment to office. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

