<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Proposal on Altering Paldiski Status Accepted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2601101694 Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN in English 0755 GMT 
26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS2601101694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From 26 January RAHVA HAAL, p 1,2] </F>
  [Excerpts] Wednesday, January 26 -- The government decided 
to approve the Justice Ministry propositions concerning the 
changed status of Paldiski pending the elections of the local 
council. Paldiski is to be merged with Keila to form a district 
of the latter, while the surrounding areas will be turned over 
to the communities. The government also discussed the powers 
and budgets of the government special representative to 
Paldiski, Juri Tikk. 
  A closed contest, held by the Economy Ministry, will be 
declared in order to purchase surveillance equipment for the 
border guard. The Border Guard Department was allocated the 
funds for the equipment. Prime Minister Mart Laar told the news 
conference that comparatively few offers have been made for the 
land border surveillance and the final decision can be made by 
April. Although the border guard preferred the Israeli company 
"Elbit", the government decided to hold a contest. Estonia has 
coordinated the purchases with Latvia and Lithuania, Laar added. 
[passage omitted) 
  The government decided to exempt foreign loans, foreign aid, 
credits with government guarantee and goods purchased for them 
from the sales tax. The equipment for the defence forces, the 
police and border guard, as well as presents connected with 
official visits, will also be exempted from the tax. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

