<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akayev Addresses Deputies on Dual Citizenship </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2201145994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1353 GMT 22 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2201145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev believes that the 
republic's citizens can be granted the right for dual 
citizenship in accordance with bilateral agreements and should 
be not fixed as a constitutional norm. 
  He declared about this on Saturday at the opening of the 
first Kurultai (congress) of Kyrgyzstan's peoples. At the same 
time Akayev underlined that he would solve the problem of dual 
citizenship minding Russia's priority significance "as the major 
partner in all spheres." 
  According to the Kyrgyz leader, "the Russian language has 
been and remains the second one" for the republic's all peoples. 
Akayev is convinced that it is necessary "to strive for 
trilinguality which is to become the basis of mentality of 
Kyrgyzstan's single people" (saying trilinguality, Akayev 
believes that all citizens of the republic must fluently speak 
the Kyrgyz, Russian, and English languages -- Interfax). He 
pointed out that the lingual factor "should not be a dominating 
one" during educating process and job placement. 
  Akayev called formation of a maximum favorable climate for 
joint existence of all nations and citizens as a necessary 
condition to activate consolidation of all ethnic groups into 
Kyrgyzstan's "single people." After the compatriots perceive 
their multinational unity, there will appear "a public 
atmosphere of aversion to nationalism and chauvinism." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

