<F P=100> Uzbekistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Says Future `Inconceivable' Without Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601103294 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1000 GMT 
26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2601103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Addressing an international congress of 
industrialists and entrepreneurs in Tashkent, Uzbek President 
Islam Karimov said that Uzbekistan's future is inconceivable 
without Russia. 
  The president unequivocally favors the restoration and 
development of economic ties among the CIS countries and the 
states of Eastern Europe. At the same time he emphasized that 
the issue of restoring all previous interstate ties should not 
arise. 
  Karimov also noted that Russia continues - and I quote here 
- 
to play the role of a dictator with regard to countries which 
used to form the USSR. The disintegration of the ruble zone is 
a good example of this, the president of Uzbekistan claims, for 
it was at that time that Russia made its partners face the 
necessity of introducing their own currencies. 

</TEXT>

