<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Accepts Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601092294 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 0900 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2601092294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] This morning's meeting between President Yeltsin of 
the Russian Federation and Boris Fedorov in the Kremlin, which 
took less than a half hour, did not have a positive outcome. As 
you know, Fedorov refused to join the reorganized government on 
20 January, saying he would only stay on as Finance Minister if 
Vice Premier Zaveryukha and the head of the Central Bank, Viktor 
Gerashchenko, left the Cabinet of Ministers. Boris Fedorov 
declined the invitation to stay on as Minister of Finance in the 
reorganized government, justifying his refusal on the grounds 
that Boris Yeltsin's offer to him was made without regard for 
the conditions which Fedorov put forward. 
  Boris Yeltsin has accepted Boris Fedorov's resignation. 

</TEXT>

