<H3> <TI>   Rumors of Chief Prosecutor's Transfer Denied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501160094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1431 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501160094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The leader of the public relations center of the 
office of Russia's prosecutor general, Aleksandr Zvyagintsev, 
said that the rumors circulated lately by some news media to the 
effect that the Prosecutor General, Aleksey Kazannik, is to be 
transferred to the Constitutional Court, are "absolutely 
unfounded." According to him, Kazannik is engaged in routine 
work; he holds conferences on pressing problems every day; under 
his initiative his office is working on ways to improve its 
performance. The plans of Russia's prosecutor general "extend 
far into the future," Zvyagintsev stressed in an interview with 
INTERFAX. 
  According to news media allegations, the man who is likely 
to 
replace Kazannik is Aleksey Ilyushenko, chief of the control 
department in the office of Russia's president. Members of his 
department have said that "these reports are nothing but 
unconfirmed rumors." Ilyushenko himself is currently on 
vacation. 

</TEXT>

