<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yazov Says Coup Attempt `Unconstitutional' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501185894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1640 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501185894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Belskiy] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 25 TASS -- Former Soviet Defence 
Minister Dmitriy Yazov, one of the 1991 August failed coup 
leaders, now tried for high treason admitted on Tuesday that the 
coup attempt was unconstitutional. 
  Yazov also admitted the unconstitutionality of the measures 
taken against Former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev who was 
removed from power and isolated at his Black Sea dacha. 
However, he stressed once again that these measures were 
necessary and aimed at preventing the Soviet Union from 
disintegration which, as he believes, would have been inevitable 
if a federal treaty had been signed by six instead of 15 
republics. 
  He said the reasons for declaring a state of emergency in 
the 
former Soviet Union were extraordinary and much stronger than 
was envisaged by the Law on the State of Emergency. 
  The former defence minister regretted that the number of 
troops brought into the city on August 19, 1991 to help police 
ensure the state of emergency was too small. At the same time 
he added that no combat orders had been issued to the troops. 
  Yazov stressed that he personally ordered the troops on high 
alert, but denied he had ordered Soviet air forces on full 
combat readiness. He noted that all orders to the troops had 
been sent by the command of the airborne troops, who, 
apparently, have overstepped their powers. 
  The court ruled that all materials of investigation obtained 
from Yazov in absence of his lawyer shall be excluded from court 
hearings. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

