<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Meteor-3' Satellite Launched </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501142194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1412 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow January 25 TASS -- A Meteor-3 meteorological 
satellite was launched by the Tsyklon rocket-booster on January 
25, 1994, from the Plesetsk space launching grounds. 
  The satellite carries Russian-made equipment to obtain 
meteorological and gelio-geophysical information, as well as a 
French-made Scarab device to measure radiation balance of the 
earth and a German-made Prare navigation system to measure 
parameters of the spacecraft motion. 
  The satellite was put into the orbit with the following 
parameters: 
  -- the initial period of rotation -- 109.4 minutes; 
  -- the maximum distance from the earth surface (in the 
apogee) -- 1,221 kilometers; 
  -- the minimum distance from the earth surface (in the 
perigee) -- 1,198 kilometers; 
  -- the inclination of the orbit -- 82.6 degrees. 
  The on-board equipment is functioning normally. The 
control-measurement complex controls the satellite's flight. 
  Information from the Meteor-3 satellite is received by the 
Russian Federal Service for Hydro-Meteorology and Environmental 
Monitoring for processing and use. 
  Alongside with the satellite, they launched a German tubsat 
small detached satellite to test the system of precise 
orientation with the help of star and solar sensors. Parameters 
of its orbit are close to the parameters of the Meteor-3. 
  The Meteor-3 launch commemorated chief designer V. Adasko. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-57435 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov016_b_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-016 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin May Offer Fedorov Post of Economic Adviser </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501111994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1108 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2501111994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 25 TASS -- A meeting of the Russian 
president and Finance Minister Boris Fedorov, who refused to 
work in the new government, is expected to take place on 
Wednesday morning and Fedorov may be offered to become the 
economic adviser of the president, TASS learned from 
well-informed sources in the presidential administration on 
Tuesday. 
  According to the sources, the post of the economic adviser 
may be instituted in the near future and it is not ruled out 
that Boris Yeltsin may offer it to Fedorov. The post envisages 
work in the government as an expert or an observer. 
  The necessity of introducing the post and possible 
candidates 
to fill it in may also be discussed at the planned meeting, the 
source said. 
  However, it is also possible that Yeltsin would prefer to 
keep Fedorov in the State Duma where the reformer can work on 
anti-inflation decisions. As a presidential aide, Fedorov will 
have to give up his parliamentary mandate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

